<DOCNO> AP881229-0012 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
it will be months before the agriculture 
department begins to estimate the size of 1989 farm crops but 
analysts are watching carefully how weather and conditions shape up 
effects of the savage 1988 drought and moisturesapping heat are 
still being felt in corn belt areas badly deficient in subsoil 
moisture corn and soybeans wont be planted until spring so 
theres some leeway 
but for winter wheat farmers who planted their 1989 crop this 
fall the crunch is on right now and in parts of the great plains 
the news is far from encouraging 
winter wheat fields in kansas continued to show signs of 
moisture stress the governments joint agricultural weather 
facility said wednesday greenbug infestation was a continuing 
problem 
texas farmers have been spraying to control the greenbugs and 
much of the winter wheat crop in the state also is hurting from lack 
of moisture 
in colorado the wheat crop was in mostly good condition 
during the week of dec 1925 but more snow cover was needed the 
report said montanas winter wheat was reported in mostly fair to 
good shape and the oregon crop was said to be in mostly good 
condition although russian wheat aphids continued to be a problem 
in the eastern part of the state 
the farm weather facility is operated by the agriculture and 
commerce departments 
on jan 13 the usda will issue a report showing how many acres of 
winter wheat farmers planted for the 1989 harvest and there will be 
projections of potential harvest output based on past trends 
weather indications and other factors however the departments 
first official 1989 winter wheat production estimate will not be 
ready until may 
meanwhile reports such as the one issued by commerce and usda 
are sifted carefully by trading interests and others for signs of 
what the future may bring 
some other observations in wednesdays report included 
the texas cotton harvest was 97 percent complete by christmas 
14 percentage points ahead of the fiveyear average for this time of 
the season 
peanut harvesting in texas was virtually complete 
north carolinas soybean harvest was about 96 percent complete 
tobacco bed preparation continued in the south in kentucky 
recent rains brought burley tobacco into case and stripping 
resumed 
floridas citrus groves were in mostly good condition 
