<TEXT>
the presidential panel charged with the task of 
recommending which military bases to close was conceived in a 1983 
report by a group of private businessmen on how the government could 
save money 
that 1983 group headed by industrialist wr grace proposed a 
nonpartisan commission to review the nations base structure and 
suggest which should be shut down 
the idea was to take congress out of the picture as much as 
possible because of the reluctance on capitol hill to permit bases 
to be closed shuttered installations mean lost jobs among voters 
and congress has blocked any base closings since 1977 
the grace panels proposal was received unenthusiastically in 
congress but in 1987 rep dick armey rtexas tried to win 
approval for the commission his amendment to a pentagon budget bill 
failed by seven votes 
armey was undaunted and spent much of the following winter 
rounding up support with congress under pressure to cut federal 
spending because of rising budget deficits there were predictions 
that closing unneeded bases could save as much as 5 billion a year 
defense secretary frank c carlucci signed on to the armey plan 
and appointed a commission last summer to begin work 
but congress delayed final approval until early october shortly 
before adjourning for the year the measure passed by congress and 
signed into law by president reagan created a 12member commission 
and a complicated procedure designed by armey and other supporters 
of closing bases as a way to circumvent congressional pressure 
once carlucci has received the panels recommendations he will 
have until jan 15 five days before he leaves office to either 
accept or reject the entire list carlucci cannot pick from among 
the list which is expected to recommend closing two dozen or more 
of the nations largest facilities 
if carlucci approves the list congress will have 45 legislative 
days starting march 1 to try to block it for that to happen both 
the house and senate would have to pass a disapproval resolution 
but that could be vetoed by george bush that means the resolution 
would need the twothirds support in each chamber required to 
override a veto 
the baseclosing commission has grouped all installations by 
military mission such as air force fighter bases and navy ports for 
surface ships then five factors will be used to define a 
facilitys military value including 
how well a base can fulfill its purpose for deployment of troops 
availability of physical facilities including runways storage 
areas and warehouses 
the physical condition and technical sophistication of those 
facilities 
quality of life for personnel and their families at the base 
community support including transportation utilities related 
industrial activities and technical help 
bases within a certain group such as air force fighter bases 
were ranked using those five criteria lowerranking bases were 
considered for closure if higherranking facilities could take over 
their duties 
other factors also were considered including cost evaluations of 
the money to be saved by closing a particular base environmental 
factors such as disposal of hazardous waste and the impact on the 
community of lost jobs 
</TEXT>
