judging by previous crashes in which bombing 
was suspected authorities investigating the pan american flight 103 
disaster may need a lucky break in the case to apprehend those who 
carried out the sabotage 
british authorities said wednesday that from examining wreckage 
they had gathered conclusive evidence that a bomb blew up the 
pan am boeing 747 jumbo jet over southern scotland last week 
spokesman john boyd said scotland yard and the fbi had joined forces 
in a criminal inquiry of international dimensions 
the challenge of finding those responsible is illustrated by 
looking at two crashes widely blamed on bombing the nov 29 1987 
crash of a korean air boeing 707 off the coast of burma and the 
plunge of an airindia 747 into the irish sea on june 22 1985 the 
korean air crash killed 115 people while the airindia tragedy 
claimed 329 lives 
in the incident involving korean air flight 858 suspicion 
quickly focused on two passengers a man and a woman who were 
detained for questioning about forged japanese passports in bahrain 
as they were about to board a plane for rome they had left the 
doomed korean aircraft bound from baghdad to bangkok at an 
intermediary stop in abu dhabi 
