<TEXT>
many disabled veterans may be missing out on 
hundreds of dollars worth of benefits from the veterans 
administration because the payments are calculated with outdated 
medical standards according to a congressional study 
the va responding to the report wednesday by the general 
accounting office said it has agreed to make the first 
comprehensive overhaul of the medical standards since 1945 
the standards have been updated on a piecemeal basis over the 
past few decades the report said but they still fail to take into 
account many medical advances 
as a result the gao said many veterans may be over or 
undercompensated for injuries that occurred both during military 
duty and afterward 
va cannot ensure that veterans are given accurate and uniform 
disability ratings because the rating schedule has not been adjusted 
to incorporate the results of many recent medical advances the 
study said 
the va paid about 143 billion in disability benefits to about 
38 million veterans and their survivors in 1987 said the gao the 
investigative branch of congress 
it is inherently difficult to achieve uniform and accurate 
administration of this type of program outofdate rating schedules 
make it almost impossible according to the report 
some medical conditions are not listed in the schedule which 
means a va rating specialist must use his or her own judgment to 
classify the disability the report said 
veterans administrator thomas k turnage responding to the 
study said he would prepare a plan for a methodical review of 
the rating schedule and added that he agreed with a recommendation 
that the schedule be reviewed regularly from now on 
the department of defense said it agreed with the reports 
findings 
a 1983 internal study by the va used 13 sample cases representing 
23 separate disabilities for which veterans already had been awarded 
compensation benefits those cases were sent to 56 of the 58 va 
regional offices to be classified 
in one case a veteran with hypertensive heart disease was 
assigned five different ratings ranging from 10 percent disability 
to 100 percent twentyfive rating boards gave him a 30 percent 
disability or 202 per month in benefits and 21 boards gave him 60 
percent or 516 in benefits 
in another case a veteran with post traumatic stress disorder 
was rated from zero to 70 percent disabled by the various boards 
which would have meant anywhere from no benefits to 410 a month 
the report said 
in a gao survey of 383 va rating specialists 61 percent said it 
was somewhat likely or very likely that in rating mental 
disorders they could reach two or more rating percentages with the 
same medical evidence 
fiftyone percent said the same situation could occur in rating 
neurological and convulsive disorders and for all types of illness 
22 percent said it was likely to reach more than one conclusion with 
the same medical evidence 
</TEXT>
