the government filed a 823 million suit 
against ei du pont de nemours amp co accusing the chemicals giant 
of helping produce gasoline containing too much lead at a new jersey 
refinery from 1983 through 1985 
the company a major supplier of lead compounds said the suit 
was without merit because it was not subject to the regulations 
it is accused of violating 
the environmental protection agency said a complaint filed 
wednesday in us district court in newark nj charged that a 
joint venture of du pont and three other companies put 2 billion 
grams too much lead 2200 tons in gasoline blended at carteret 
nj 
the government seeks the maximum fine of 10000 a day for each 
of the 823 days specified in the complaint 
epa in 1986 filed an administrative complaint against du pont but 
was unable to reach a settlement with the company 
in wilmington del company spokesman tom barry read a statement 
from jerry mccleskey planning director of the companys chemicals 
and pigments department charging that epas action was without 
merit 
the allegations are false we will contest the novel and 
strained interpretation of the regulations we complied fully with 
all regulations applicable to lead suppliers and cannot be held 
responsible for alleged violations by others mccleskey said 
later barry himself said it was simply not a fact that the 
operation was a joint venture as epa said 
du pont said it was only a supplier but epa contended that du 
pont decided how much lead was to be used injected the compound at 
the blending plant determined that the final product was suitable 
for sale as leaded gasoline and advised the other participants in 
the venture about epa regulations 
the activities in effect made du pont a refiner subject to the 
refining regulations and just as responsible for the excess lead as 
any of the other parties epa said 
the agency filed administrative complaints against the other 
three companies two of which are now inactive the third a 
tarricone inc a new york petroleum marketer is operating under 
protection of the bankruptcy courts and epa said it had filed a 
claim against that company in the bankruptcy case 
lead is the cheapest way to increase gasoline octane but high 
concentrations in auto emissions can cause neurological damage to 
children and may contribute to high blood pressure in adults it 
also damages pollution control equipment in cars not designed for 
leaded gasoline 
epa has been ordering lower concentrations of lead in leaded 
gasoline for years the 1982 limit of 11 gram per gallon was 
reduced to 05 gram on july 1 1985 and 01 gram on jan 1 1986 
the 2 billion grams of excessive lead added by the carteret plant 
would amount to about 2 percent of all lead used in fuels in 
19831985 according to epa estimates 
