<TEXT>
the agriculture department is considering new 
federal labeling and processing rules to ensure that certain kinds 
of meat patties including precooked hamburgers are safe to eat 
lester m crawford administrator of the departments food safety 
and inspection service said there has been increasing evidence 
over the past several years that disease organisms survive in 
products that many consumers erroneously believe are fully cooked 
when bought 
the proposal would affect fully cooked partially cooked and 
charmarked ground meat patties 
crawford said examples include such items as charbroiled beef 
patties and prebrowned fresh pork sausage patties 
as these types of covenenience products continue to become more 
popular we must establish requirements to reduce the potential for 
foodborne illnesses he said 
recently crawford said a strain of bacteria escherichia coli 
was linked to an outbreak of food poisoning which hospitalized six 
minnesota school children with severe diarrhea and cramps 
crawford said the centers for disease control determined that 
undercooked beef patties caused the illness although the specific 
strain of bacteria that infected the children has not been isolated 
from the patties 
the proposed rule would establish requirements for the storage of 
raw ingredients processing times and temperatures handling to 
prevent contamination after processing and labels that include 
cooking instruction for final preparation 
for example he said the partially cooked ground meat patties 
would bear the label statement partially cooked for safety cook 
until well done internal temperature of 160 f 
public comments on the proposal can be sent by jan 27 to policy 
office linda carey hearing clerk fsis usda washington dc 
20250 
