<TEXT>
q congressman les aspin dwis chairman of the house armed 
services committee suggested that there was a loophole in this 
whole procedure and that funds had to be appropriated annually to 
close these bases and by use of that loophole bases could be 
prevented from being closed did you address that question and what 
did you do about it 
edwards there is a problem because the proceeds of the sales of 
these facilities will go into the fund to carry out the purposes of 
this law and those proceeds are not going to start coming in on day 
one its going to take a while to come in and so we have 
recommended in this report that congress in fiscal 1990 
appropriate 300 million to put the first money in the fund so we 
can start the process and obviously if congress refuses to 
appropriate enough money to get the process going then its 
going to be very difficult 
q its often said that certain bases have remained open over the 
years for political or pork barrel reasons did you find any 
evidence of that in your study and how far have you gone to 
eliminating it if thats the case 
ribicoff i dont think there was any influence or any attempt to 
protect pork barrel bases i dont think that was taken into account 
at all i dont think anybody on the commission felt any pressure 
we looked at these bases seriously we looked at all the figures we 
spent a lot of time in discussion each and every base was voted on 
unanimously with the action taken 
edwards you should understand first that we simply did not start 
with a list we started with a set of criteria which we applied 
to all 4300 installations in this country and we took those as 
we found them 
q there are four states that are missing west virginia 
mississippi georgia and wisconsin all home states of the chairmen 
of the armed services and appropriations committees were there no 
bases in those states worthy of closing 
edwards thats certainly not by design we did take a little 
something out of fort mcpherson in georgia i recall i dont 
believe we touched wisconsin west virginia im going to bet 
doesnt have a whole lot of military in the first place we had 
to deal with bases where we found them 
q could you please elaborate on some of the personnel changes 
that are going to take place at fort devens and some of the other 
bases that are getting increases of people 
ribicoff we found that certain missions were split between a 
number of bases they didnt make any sense when they should have 
been consolidated and put in one base and what we did in many 
instances we just do that and especially when you talk about fort 
devens you will find a shift from one fort to the other one 
base to the other which will make it more effective more 
efficient and be able to do a much better job with their mission 
q i wonder if you had the opportunity to pass judgment on the 
value of strategic home porting to see whether dispersion of ships 
offers protection in the nuclear age or whether its really just a 
way of building local political support for various naval tasks 
edwards i dont know anything that was discussed more than 
strategic home porting we concluded that our job was not to 
deal with force structure thats the militarys job our job 
was to try to deal with that force structure as we found it and try 
to accommodate it to the facilities that we were working with and 
so we had to live with the fact that theres going to be a 600ship 
navy maybe there never will be but we dont know that 
so we had to look at the home ports with an idea where are you 
going to put that other 150 ships that are building up from the 
450ship navy and we concluded that we could justify some home 
ports most of them 
q if it were not for political constraints could you actually 
expand your list are there a lot of other bases you consider 
still vulnerable or could be effectively closed 
edwards the biggest constraint is the sixyear payback 
constraint we found a lot of facilities that had 10year paybacks 
12year paybacks even 20year paybacks where we could have made 
some major savings over a longer period of time but we were 
constrained by our charter which had a sixyear payback 
ribicoff once you got over the six years we had to stop i 
think wisdom and better planning would have been more meaningful if 
we werent stuck with that sixyear payback 
q in other words some of these places survived because of 
their inefficiency 
edwards no i think it may cost a lot of money to move one 
facility into another base and have to build allnew construction 
and your payback just simply wont make it 
