<DOCNO> AP881229-0099 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a government commission called thursday for 
closing 34 military installations including five major air force 
bases and the armys secondlargest basic training site in a 
recommendation that could send economic shock waves to communities 
across america 
in addition the commission on base realignment and closure 
recommended closing 52 military housing units in 13 states that date 
back to the construction of nike missile bases in the 1950s and 
partially closing five military facilities and changing the mission 
and the manpower levels at 54 other facilities 
the panels recommendations appeared to have a good chance of 
taking effect if defense secretary frank c carlucci approves them 
as expected congress would have to reject the whole list in order 
to save any of the facilities and even such a resolution of 
disapproval could be vetoed by presidentelect george bush after he 
moves into the white house on jan 20 
carlucci who has strongly supported the work of the bipartisan 
commission has until jan 15 five days before leaving office to 
either accept or reject the entire list 
the first overhaul in 11 years of the nations web of 3800 
military installations could save an estimated 693 million a year 
without hindering the national security said abraham ribicoff a 
former democratic senator from connecticut and cochairman of the 
panel 
the 693 million savings is minuscule when compared with the 
pentagons annual budget of 300 billion 
the states hit hardest by the panels recommendations were 
california which would lose five major installations and illinois 
which would lose two the area of the nation faring best was the 
south which wouldnt lose any major facilities 
the five air force bases recommended for closure include chanute 
in illinois george mather and norton in california and pease in 
new hampshire their missions would be shifted to other bases 
also closed would be the presidio a major army administrative 
base in san francisco and fort douglas in utah a facility built in 
1862 to protect pony express riders from indians it has often been 
cited as a prime example of unneeded bases 
the five bases that would be partially shut down include fort 
dix nj where 33490 recruits underwent basic training in the 
year that ended sept 30 only fort jackson sc trains more 
recruits fort dix would go on semiactive status at a loss of 4686 
military and civilian jobs 
fiftyfour other bases should be realigned meaning they would 
either gain or lose personnel the commission said 
also closed would be part of fort meade md and the 
philadelphia naval hospital which the navy has long wanted to shut 
down 
the panel called for halting construction at three sites where 
the navy wanted to built new ports for its growing fleet of ships 
and closing the sites they are the hunters point naval station in 
san francisco the galveston texas naval station and the lake 
charles la naval station 
the early reaction from congress was generally positive sen sam 
nunn dga chairman of the senate armed services committee said 
the odds are heavily in favor of the list becoming law 
my general feeling is this will be well received by the 
congress he said nunns state would not lose any major bases 
sen john warner rva ranking republican on the armed services 
committee agreed i think the recommendation will make it all the 
way through he said 
but sens alan dixon and paul simon both illinois democrats 
noted their state is losing chanute air force base and the armys 
fort sheridan they complained that overseas bases should be closed 
before any us facilities are mothballed 
ribicoff and panel cochairman jack edwards a former republican 
congressman from alabama predicted some legislators would be 
unhappy but said congress isnt likely to overturn the decision 
legislators with bases on the reduction list are going to be 
unhappy and we understand that said edwards but we feel like 
the majority of the house and senate will support what we have 
done 
local communities will be unhappy edwards said of course 
they will have a hard time swallowing the decision in some 
communities a military base provides a source of employment and a 
sure source of income in good times and bad 
edwards said he was sympathetic with communities that would lose 
facilities because an air force base closed in his district 25 years 
ago costing 14000 jobs i certainly understand the impact he 
said 
closed bases mean lost jobs and congress has refused to permit 
any major closures since 1977 when the first of a thicket of rules 
and regulations was enacted to make it hard for the pentagon to pare 
down the installation list 
the 12member panel was created this year as a way to circumvent 
such congressional roadblocks and there were predictions the annual 
savings might be as high as 2 billion to 5 billion 
the savings estimate provided by the commission does fall short 
of the savings estimates which many had predicted nunn said 
but hayden b bryan executive director of the panel said those 
early estimates were just pulled out of the air 
the panel working in strict secrecy considered a number of 
factors including military utility and whether a bases functions 
could be better carried out at another location 
another requirement was that the onetime costs of closing a 
base such as severance pay and waste cleanup would be offset 
within six years by the money that would be saved 
our report represents an opportunity to reduce training costs 
in terms of manpower overhead costs and fuel to improve command 
and control consolidate training and improve economies of scale and 
to remove unnecessary administrative burdens to our defense 
managers edwards said 
two installations loring air force base in maine and virginias 
fort monroe escaped even though they have long been included on 
critics lists of unneeded bases it was the air forces attempt to 
close loring in 1977 which prompted the congressional roadblocks to 
the pentagons base realignment efforts 
fort monroe was originally built with a moat to protect us 
forces from british attack in the war of 1812 
edwards said loring and fort monroe escaped the ax because they 
have developed new uses in recent years meaning they didnt met the 
commissions complicated set of criteria for closing a base 
while some of the 34 bases that would be closed are major 
installations with big payrolls others are far smaller 
installations 
the latter include such places as fort wingate a new mexico site 
where the army stores ammunition and which employs only 92 people 
the armys tacony warehouse in philadelphia and hamilton army 
airfield near san francisco which employs only 29 people and is 
used only as a training center for reservists 
</TEXT>
