the agriculture department said thursday it 
will establish offices at each of 17 historically black universities 
to help encourage more minorities to enter agriculture and forestry 
deputy secretary peter c myers said the offices will be a 
focal point for all usda activities at the universities 
collectively known as 1890 institutions because of landgrant 
college legislation that year 
a few department agencies have offices at some of those schools 
but myers said this will be the first time that there will be an 
oncampus link between usda and each of the universities 
myers said the offices will help with curriculum development 
recruit and counsel students on employment opportunities in usda 
and develop new ideas and approaches to help smallscale 
limitedresource and minority farmers 
from international trade to the revitalization of rural 
america there are numerous career opportunities in agriculture and 
forestry he said usda is strengthening its ties to the 1890 
institution to ensure that minority youth know of those 
opportunities and are encouraged to seek out careers in 
agriculture 
myers said usda is recruiting among current employees for the 
liaison offices and expects to have all positions filled by april 
the 17 institutions are 
