<TEXT>
romanian leader nicolae ceausescu said 
in a rare interview with a western newspaper that his controversial 
plan to raze 7000 villages is needed to modernize the countryside 
in a related development a frankfurtbased human rights 
organization said romanian border police this year have killed at 
least 400 romanians many of hungarian or german descent trying to 
flee to yugoslavia 
among the villages to be razed under ceausescus plan are most of 
those where ethnic hungarians or germans form a majority of the 
local population 
the bonn daily newspaper die welt said the autocratic communist 
party ruler spoke in a recent interview in bucharest romanias 
capital die welt released excerpts of the interview to news 
agencies before its publication friday 
our villages should systematically take on a new appearance 
ceausescu was quoted as saying romanians in the third millenium 
must belong to a nation with a higher living standard enjoyed by 
each citizen in equal measure 
ceausescu last spring revealed plans for destroying about 7000 
of romanias 13000 villages and resettling residents in housing 
complexes attached to agroindustrial centers 
the plan is aimed at providing more farmland and at modernizing 
the agricultural industry but it has drawn criticism from east and 
west 
foreign critics including former us ambassador david 
funderburk contend ceausescu is trying to wipe out the vestiges of 
romanias capitalist and religious past 
last month the romanian leader appeared to back down somewhat 
from his announcement the villages would disappear under his 
resettlement plan he said at the time that some communes in rural 
romania would be preserved to avoid depopulating the countryside 
in the die welt interview ceausescu reiterated that those who 
want to stay in their village homes will be allowed to 
but he contended that a systematic consolidation of rural 
residents into agricultural centers is necessary to improve living 
conditions transport and labor productivity 
ceausescu has said the relocation project should be completed by 
2000 
so far only scattered villages near the capital bucharest have 
been razed but the policy has caused widespread disruption in the 
countryside and disturbed relations with foreign countries 
particularly allied hungary 
the international society for human rights in frankfurt said 
thursday that the romanianyugoslavian border is the bloodiest in 
europe 
romanians have attempted to flee the country in droves and at 
least 400 have been shot and killed by romanian border police in the 
past year the private human rights group said in a dispatch to news 
media 
it said an even larger number of romanians drowned while trying 
to escape by swimming the danube which borders the two countries 
but it did not give a figure 
the society said many of those who succeeded in reaching 
yugoslavia were sent back to romania unless the refugees managed to 
contact united nations authorities in belgrade 
in budapest hungary the commander of hungarys border guards 
said 6974 romanians have tried to cross illegally into hungary this 
year a fourfold increase over last year 
but the commander janos szekely disputed reports that hundreds 
of romanians attempting to flee to hungary were shot and killed by 
romanian border guards 
an estimated 30000 romanians most of them ethnic hungarians 
have found refuge in hungary which in january took the 
unprecedented step of accepting refugees from a fellow warsaw pact 
country 
szekely said 1400 romanians who fled illegally into hungary were 
returned to romania but he said they were undesirables such as 
common criminals vagrants and teenage delinquents 
die welt also quoted ceausescu as rejecting the reforms of soviet 
president mikhail s gorbachev as a model for other socialist 
nations 
there is no model no stencil for development in the socialist 
world ceausescu was quoted as saying each nation must 
differentiate itself in this way 
the newspaper said ceausescu also rejected suggestions that his 
efforts to pay off foreign loans have harshly affected living 
conditions in romania including widespread shortages of power food 
and consumer goods 
he acknowledged a few difficulties but he said the 
government has brought prices under control and expects a stable 
energy situation in two years 
