<TEXT>
some instruments have failed on board a satellite 
headed for the martian moon phobos but the mission is not in 
jeopardy the soviet news agency tass reported thursday 
the soviets have lost the first of the pair of probes phobos i 
and phobos ii heading for mars reports from the united states this 
week said the second satellite also was experiencing problems 
putting the entire project in danger 
routine equipment checks revealed isolated malfunctions in some 
of the instruments on board phobos ii tass said 
but it quoted garri rogovsky of the babakin research and testing 
center in kaliningrad as saying that most have been rectified 
while the rest wont prevent the research program from being carried 
out in full 
phobos i was launched on july 7 but in september a wrong 
computer command caused it to stop responding to commands from earth 
and it was lost 
phobos ii launched days later continues on course toward mars 
it is to enter a mars orbit late next month and approach the moon 
phobos in april 
its package of instruments and experiments were prepared by a 
group of 12 countries and by the european space agency but the 
project is especially valuable to the soviet union because soviet 
scientists are aiming for a manned mission to mars early in the 21st 
century 
tass said phobos i and phobos ii carried almost identical 
equipment but the lost probe carried instruments to register 
neutron radiation from phobos surface and to study mars magnetic 
field not included on phobos ii 
on approaching mars phobos ii will take infrared and gamma ray 
readings compile a temperature map and data on its mineral makeup 
atmosphere and ionosphere tass said 
moving on to phobos it will drop to within 165 feet to analyze 
the martian moons soil with the help of a laser and then drop two 
small landing craft onto the moons surface 
