<TEXT>
pease air force base where george bush 
arrives when he visits maine is one of the biggest installations 
put on the chopping block thursday and officials hunted for ways to 
soften the 340 million shock 
news that the 33yearold base home to some of the countrys top 
bomber groups might close as soon as january 1990 shocked many 
people in the state 
the base employs 3700 military personnel and 500 civilians 
there also are an estimated 1700 secondary jobs stemming from the 
base and the closing is expected to cost 340 million to the 
economy within a 100mile radius 
base commander col orin godsey said local officials were 
amazed and i dont think they expected it when he met with them 
to break the news its like a lot of other communities in the 
united states today because no one ever wants to think they will be 
on the closure list 
the commission on base realignment and closure proposed that 34 
military installations be closed it also recommended partially 
closing five other bases and reorganizing 54 more that would get new 
missions and additional personnel 
godsey said despite the shock local officials had a very 
positive outlook theyre looking at ways they can make the military 
base a usable installation 
one of the most frequently mentioned ideas was to convert the 
base into a regional airport 
the states congressional delegation who supported creation of 
the commission said they would not fight the closing if it is 
justified 
i dont want to raise false expectations about altering this 
recommendation said sen gordon humphrey a conservative 
republican at this juncture it looks like a foregone conclusion 
that it will close its highly unlikely that congress will reject 
this list 
if theres a good case to be made to close pease so be it 
military bases arent forever 
rep robert smith another conservative republican said he and 
the rest of the delegation planned to meet with people in the state 
to acertain their feelings if they want me to fight it ill 
fight it he said 
the commission recommended closing pease because of a shortage of 
facilities at the base and its vulnerability to sublaunched 
ballistic missiles that could strike before its planes get off the 
ground the panel said 
pease opened in 1956 and has been home of the 509th bombardment 
wing whose predecessor the 509th composite group of the army air 
corps dropped the bomb on hiroshima 
in 1985 pease was listed in the book nuclear battlefields as 
having 190 atomic warheads ranking new hampshire 21st among the 
states the federal government does not acknowledge where it keeps 
its nuclear weapons 
since its founding pease has been a base for b29 b52 and b47 
bombers today it deploys kc135 refueling tankers and fb111 
fighter bombers 
