<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration said 
thursday it is requiring tightened security by us air carriers at 
103 airports in the middle east and western europe including xray 
or physical inspection of all checked baggage and random physical 
checks of some carryon baggage 
the new measures coming in the wake of the dec 21 bombing of 
pan am flight 103 which killed all 259 people on board and 11 people 
on the ground in lockerbie scotland will be effective within 48 
hours and far exceed existing international standards said faa 
administrator t allan mcartor 
many of the new measures already are being followed but until 
now had not been required all the time he said 
the new measures may well result in passenger delays and 
inconvenience mcartor said adding that they could mean 
checkin earlier perhaps as much as an hour 
mcartor said he was not at liberty to discuss how passengers 
would be selected for random inspection of handbaggage or what 
proportion would be chosen for those inspections 
asked why similar measures were not being required at us 
airports mcartor told a news conference the threat appears to be 
more international in scope we are encouraging our carriers to be 
more vigilant domestically 
in addition to the 100 percent inspection of checked baggage and 
the random inspection of carryon baggage here are the main points 
of the faas new program 
passengers may not have access to checked baggage after it has 
cleared security 
airlines must perform positive match of passenger and 
baggage to keep unaccompanied bags off the plane asked what would 
happen if a passenger boarded a plane in frankfurt with a ticket to 
new york but departed the plane at a stop in london ray salazar 
director of the faas office of civil aviation said that persons 
baggage would have to be removed from the plane in london in 
accordance with the already required reconciliation at the 
transfer gate of the passenger and baggage manifests 
additional measures will be required to preclude unauthorized 
access to baggage mcartor did not say what these additional 
measures would be 
parcels shipped through passenger ticket counters also must be 
xrayed or physically examined 
the faa is accelerating by six months the delivery of thermal 
neutron analysis devices which are capable of detecting all known 
explosives even those that are transparent to xrays such as the 
plastic explosives favored by terrorists under the accelerated 
program the first unit will be in operation next summer and the 
last of five perhaps six will be operational by the beginning of 
1990 
mcartor said it had not been decided where to place the thermal 
neutron equipment which could go into airports either in the united 
states or overseas or a combination of the two each unit costs 
750000 to 1 million 
the agencys security inspection staff will be increased by 22 
percent from 550 people to 670 over the next 20 months 
the faa had not computed any estimates of additional costs to the 
airlines for the tightened security arrangements said agency 
spokeswoman joann sloane 
stephen hayes a spokesman for the air transport association an 
organization of the major us air carriers said the airline 
industry will comply fully with the new security initiatives 
however more must be done than simply placing additional 
security requirements on the airlines hayes said the 
government itself must become more directly involved in meeting the 
threat that international terrorism presents 
we believe the faa should assign more of its security personnel 
to europe and the middle east and we believe the faa should impose 
the same security requirements on foreign airlines which serve the 
united states as it imposes on us airlines he said 
mcartor said the new measures overlap and duplicate to a certain 
extent precautions ordered by the british authorities at heathrow 
airport near london that took effect thursday and are quite 
similar to the procedures of el al the best in the world 
el al is the israeli national carrier known for its rigorous 
security precautions it has never suffered a midair explosion 
in april 1986 an arab terrorist gave his unsuspecting girlfriend 
a bomb to carry onto an el al jetliner bound from london to israel 
the plastic explosive was discovered by an israeli security guard at 
heathrow 
ms sloane the faa spokeswoman said the faa did not anticipate 
imposing any additional training requirements for security personnel 
hired by us airlines domestically or overseas 
