<TEXT>
the california supreme court citing the 
need for commercial stability on thursday limited the right of 
wrongfully fired employees to collect big damage awards 
the ruling by the conservativedominated court moved away from 
the course the california judiciary has taken since 1980 when a 
court then controlled by liberals led the nation in restricting an 
employers right to fire at will 
the court ruled 43 that a worker who is fired without good 
cause in violation of a companys express or implied promise can 
sue only for reinstatement and back pay not for emotional distress 
and punitive damages 
initially predictability of the consequences of actions 
related to employment contracts is important to commercial 
stability wrote chief justice malcolm lucas in the majority 
decision 
in order to achieve such stability it is also important that 
employers not be unduly deprived of discretion to dismiss an 
employee by the fear that doing so will give rise to potential tort 
recovery for additional damages in every case the opinion said 
the court allowed employees to seek additional damages when their 
firings involved violations of public policy such as a workers 
refusal to break a law 
justice allen broussard who wrote one of three dissenting 
opinions accused the majority of a radical attempt to rewrite 
california law in a way that will leave wrongfully fired workers 
without adequate relief 
this court is only concerned with stability of the corporation 
and not the slightest bit with stability of everyday working 
people said cliff palefsky a lawyer for employees and labor 
unions 
victor schachter an employers attorney said the ruling 
provides a welcome bridle to unwarranted and costly termination 
claims 
the ruling reinstates but sharply limits a suit by daniel foley 
who was fired from his 56164ayear job as los angeles branch 
manager of interactive data corp in 1983 after telling the company 
that his boss was being investigated by the fbi for embezzlement 
from a former employer 
lucas said foley could sue only on the grounds that his 
encouraging treatment during nearly seven years of employment may 
have amounted to a promise that he wouldnt be fired without good 
cause 
under thursdays ruling his damages would be limited to lost pay 
since the courts 1980 ruling allowing wrongfultermination 
suits more than 40 other states have allowed some types of claims 
by fired workers 
but few have gone as far as california appellate court rulings 
allowing emotional distress and punitive damages for workers 
wrongfully fired 
those rulings were repudiated by the court majority thursday 
most plaintiffs are managerial employees union members generally 
cannot sue but must seek reinstatement through their labor 
contracts 
about 1000 wrongfultermination suits were filed statewide in 
1986 studies have shown employees winning about twothirds of the 
cases that go to trial with damages averaging 177000 for 120 
winning plaintiffs in a 198086 rand corp survey 
</TEXT>
