<TEXT>
two federal courts cleared way thursday for 
the setting of a statewide date for election of trial judges 
delayed for years by lawsuits charging racial discrimination 
state attorney general mike moore said the court action would end 
the piecemeal fashion in which mississippi voters elect chancery 
and circuit judges by allowing one general election on june 20 in 
which blacks would have a fair chance of being elected 
now i dont think mississippi is discriminatory and i think it 
is time we stood up and showed it moore said 
no black has been elected a judge in mississippi without first 
being appointed as a result blacks challenged judicial election 
practices in lawsuits filed in 1984 and 1985 and some judges whose 
terms expired have remained in office awaiting court action on an 
election date 
the action thursday involved the signing of final drafts of 
proposed orders in two separate courts officials said 
carroll rhodes a lawyer in hazlehurst who represents black 
plaintiffs in the fouryearold lawsuit said an agreement had been 
reach to allow federal courts in both mississippi and washington to 
move quickly to close out all pending cases and appeals dealing with 
the election of chancery and circuit judges 
under the agreement primary elections will be held statewide 
april 4 for the judgeships with the general election on june 20 
rhodes said earlier elections in about half the districts had been 
scheduled in february and april 
us district judge william h barbour jr signed an order 
delaying until june elections that would have been held in february 
in 21 districts that have not voted for judges since 1982 
under a settlement of a racial bias lawsuit already worked out by 
barbour 13 blacks had filed in those districts before a dec 9 
deadline attorneys said under the agreement filing would not be 
reopened in the 21 districts 
the other court that signed an order thursday was a panel of 
three federal judges meeting in jackson and led by the chief judge 
of the 5th us circuit court of appeals it tentatively accepted 
settlement of a similar redistricting lawsuit in which election of 
judges postbypost instead of districtwide was challenged as 
designed to dilute the voting strength of blacks 
the plan calls for redrawing 19 eastern districts to allow 
multijudge elections with a feb 28 qualifying deadline rhodes 
said he said that with all candidates running in one districtwide 
election blacks could concentrate their voting strength on one 
candidate a technique called singleshot voting that has helped 
minorities elsewhere 
the state attorney generals office said the qualifying deadline 
for the 19 districts would be scheduled to allow the legislature 
time to adopt the redistricting which must be approved first by the 
us justice department under the 1965 voting rights act 
moore said he expected rapid approval because federal 
representatives participated in negotiations in which the state 
pushed for the costsaving uniform election date and gave in on 
opposing the multijudge redistricts 
this is something new for mississippi and i think it shows 
there is progressive leadership in the state said rhodes i 
just hope this progressive leadership will continue and this will 
not be the end of it 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

