<TEXT>
a federal judge lifted a restraining order 
preventing the long island lighting co from paying stock dividends 
after the financially shaky utility agreed thursday to notify the 
court 10 days before issuing any dividends 
us district judge jack b weinstein who is presiding over the 
ratehike suit against lilco issued the restraining order in the 
morning but lifted it seven hours later 
shortly after the order was signed a company spokesman minimized 
its impact saying the company had not paid dividends since 1984 and 
had no immediate plans to resume payments 
weinstein scheduled a hearing on the issue for next wednesday 
the judge is seeking a settlement of suffolk countys successful 
civil racketeering suit against lilco an accord that could possibly 
include closing the controversial shoreham nuclear power plant 
closed negotiations have been ongoing for about two weeks 
a jury earlier this month found that the utility had lied to 
state officials about the progress of the shoreham plant to obtain 
rate increases in 1978 and 1984 the jury awarded 228 million in 
damages to suffolk 
weinstein must now decide whether to certify a class of 
ratepayers in the suit making lilco liable for at least 4 billion 
i think this is really the judge trying to assert his authority 
and to show everybody how tough hes going to be and to force the 
parties to negotiate a settlement to this whole thing said barry 
abramson a senior utilities analyst with prudentialbache 
abramson downplayed the effect the temporary order would have on 
wall street 
the actual order is not significant in my opinion because lilco 
couldnt pay the dividends anyway he said i think that lilco 
has no ability and no desire to pay any dividends in the short run 
on thursday lilco closed at 13 per share on the new york stock 
exchange up 25 cents 
the restraining order was issued in response to a request by 
judith vladeck the attorney representing the proposed class of 
ratepayers said these payments would total about 1 billion 
in view of lilcos limited net worth payment of such dividends 
would severely reduce lilcos ability to pay a judgement awarded 
to the proposed plaintiff class she wrote in an affidavit it 
would further severely impair the likelihood of achieving a fair and 
reasonable settlement on behalf of the plaintiff class 
in albany on wednesday the state public service commission 
denied lilcos request for an immediate 54 percent rate increase 
and said it would reconsider the utilitys request again on jan 25 
</TEXT>
