<DOCNO> AP881229-0205 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a group of dallas times herald employees filed suit 
thursday in us district court against the newspapers former 
owner times mirror co for failing to comply with terms of the 
company pension plan and refusing to terminate the plan and 
distribute its assets 
the suit says times mirror the los angelesbased media group 
that owned the times herald from 1969 to 1986 signed an agreement 
not to terminate or amend the pension plan at the time of its sale 
in 1986 to a media company led by william dean singleton 
the suit asks the court to stop a proposed merger of the plan and 
to distribute its assets to participants 
about 800 current and former times herald employees are covered 
in the plan the plaintiffs current and former times herald 
employees ron calhoun helen connor charles dameron cd fletcher 
jim henderson and carolyn robinson represent those covered in the 
plan 
the suit says times mirror wants to take 15 million of the 27 
million in the pension plan for its own use despite the fact that 
it has contributed less than 1 million to it for 19 years 
times mirror kept control of the plan after selling the paper to 
singleton it attempted to terminate the plan for the first time in 
july 1986 then again last april 
in august times mirror filed formal notice to terminate the plan 
and take excess funds of about 15 million but withdrew the notice 
after being notified that the plan participants claimed all excess 
assets 
in november times mirror filed notice to merge the plan with 
another employee benefits plan it controls it withdrew that notice 
dec 23 after receiving numerous complaints from participants 
times mirror referred all comment to dallas lawyer thomas 
craddock who could not be contacted late thursday 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

